  "notes": [
    {
      "id": "note_46",
      "text": "Tests whether each wired column is drawn from a normal distribution, one row per variable: the test statistic, its p-value, n, and a yes/no verdict at your chosen alpha. Shapiro-Wilk (the default, and the most powerful test; valid for 3 ≤ n ≤ 5000) is recommended; D'Agostino-Pearson (an omnibus skewness + kurtosis K² test, n ≥ 8, better for very large samples) and Jarque-Bera are also available. A small p-value means the data depart from normality, so a rank / non-parametric method is safer downstream. All three match scipy (shapiro / normaltest / jarque_bera). Shapiro & Wilk 1965; Royston 1995.",
      "x": 40,
      "y": 24,
      "width": 360,
      "height": 190
    }
